After install of 20.10 I got the notice to upgrade to 21.04, the next LTS, which is what I really wanted anyways, and I got to upgrade on a completely clean installation. /fin
Good things about all this:I realized #1, AND I also got to nuke my wonky install of openconnect (along w/ the whole system) and install that clean so everything matches up and actually works. /4

And of course the installer couldn't just install over my old partitions, so I had to run the demo off the USB, format the drives, and then install w/ creating my own partitions in the right places. /3
I realized this waaayyyy too late of course, and ended up nuking my install, which formatted all of the files and stuff I had spent yesterday afternoon and evening copying over to the new machine. /2

TIL not to change the name of a drive using Linux's "Disks" utility w/out changing it in the /etc/fstab file too, or you might get kicked to emergency boot when the system can't find the drive to mount it at boot time. /1

Full models did worse at predicting female CAD cases than male CAD cases.  Future CAD prediction studies should pay more attention to how to apply genetic risk estimates equally for both sexes - and consider lowering the threshold for treating females to 5.0% 10 year risk.  /end

As a second step, she recommends applying polygenic scores with the age and sex interactions to identify people who newly qualify as having a relatively high risk of heart disease, and then having those people initiate preventive approaches.  8/9 https://t.co/5wbRzVKOAK

Furthermore, Dr. Surakka recommends first using standard clinical models to identify people at risk of heart disease (such as ASCVD), and getting those people on preventive therapies and lifestyle changes as soon as possible.  7/9

The models with age and sex interaction terms worked best (or sex-stratified with age interaction terms). The inclusion of the interaction terms was most likely correcting for the survival bias observed in the datasets.  6/9

Then Dr. Surakka created prediction models using two cohorts ‚Äî 50k Norwegians from the HUNT study with up to 35 years of follow-up and 370k British from the UK biobank with 12 years followup ‚Äî to best predict who had a heart attack, after incorporating genetics.   5/9

‚ùì What am I working on right now? Paralogs are multiple copies of a gene. They often occur in protein complexes. I'm analyzing proteomic data to identify how one paralog responds when the other one is deleted (to try identify potential synthetic lethal relationships!) (8/8)

‚ùì What are some of these datasets? CPTAC, PCAWG, and DepMap are a few great resources. @cosmint_  posted about DepMap last week, so I'll link to the CPTAC webpage here for anyone interested to know more! (7/8)https://t.co/tHnOUB9uED

‚ùì How can we identify such relationships?Data from omics-level screens gives us a great opportunity to try and identify such relationships between protein complex members. Many such datasets are now being published by consortia around the world. (6/8)

‚ùì What's a synthetic lethal relationship? This means that when one gene is perturbed, the cell becomes dependent on another gene. Targeting this second gene or its product could then allow us to selectively target cancer cells. (5/8)

‚ùì What does this mean for cancer treatment? Understanding how complexes respond when a member is perturbed could help identify new therapeutic targets. For example, some complex members have synthetic lethal relationships. (4/8)

‚ùì What's the connection with cancer? When a gene coding for a complex member is mutated in a cancer cell, this disruption can drive cancer progression. In fact, 50% of driver gene mutations occur in complex members. (3/8)

‚ùì What is a protein complex?It's a group of proteins that interact with each other to carry out a function in the cell. Protein complexes are involved in various different processes- they're like little molecular machines! (2/8)

10/10: Our work sheds light into the high heterogeneity within chromothriptic tumors at DNA/RNA levels. We characterised specific genome rearrangements, assessed the link to double minutes mergence & found specific genetic programmes being affected. More details within the MS!
9/10: And experimentally assessed how the Inactivation of SETD2 and TP53 in neural stem cells leads to genomeinstability https://t.co/zglCSsl6K1
8/10: We studied the loss of chromosome 3p and SETD2 deficiency as early events potentially facilitating chromothripsis https://t.co/igpEyCeYWq

7/10: We developed a strategy that allowed us to integrate the DNA and RNA information layers (same tissue, different set of cells) facilitating to detect modified transcriptional programmes that are presumably affected by the CNV changes at the DNA level. https://t.co/od86yNHz02
6/10: At the transcriptional level, we characterised cell composition within samples, integrated at patient and PDX levels and detected differentially expressed genes. https://t.co/0RmJ11zl6f

5/10: We evaluated the presence of double minute chromosomes across samples, their relationship with chormotrhipsis and gene expression. Based on our data, chromothripsis is a major event for the formation of double-minute chromosomes https://t.co/0x1eHYX7zh

4/10: We designed a strategy for detecting chromothripsis at the single cell and clone levels and observed differential events at different clones, questioning the view of chromothripsis as a unique event. We observed genomic differences between clones at different timepoints https://t.co/KLY0C0NJyr

3/10: Based on single-cell CNV profiles we detected Clones & inferred lineage trees on them. This allowed us to unveil clonal heterogeneity (differential gains/losses and asymmetric divisions) that otherwise remain hidden at the bulk level. https://t.co/e5DIpkMJA6

2/10: We have generated single-cell DNA-seq CNV and single-cell/nuclei RNA-seq data both from patient tumors and PDX models. We have developed several computational approaches to perform downstream analysis on the data. https://t.co/ufMU30T4AW

I hope this tool would lower the entry barrier into covalent ligand design for non-experts. There are hundreds of predictions just waiting to be made. Go forth and make covalent inhibitors üòÅ 10/10.

Together with @covid_moonshot and @EnamineLtd we made and tested tens of UGI analogs and validated the Covalentizer prediction with tens of co-crystal structures. Thanks @MartinWalshDLS @FrankvonDelft @Darenfearon @DiamondLightSou and @barr_haim  9/n

Finally, as COVID-19 broke we searched in our already pre-calculated DB of covalent predictions for useful inhibitors. We found a covalent prediction based on an old SARS-CoV Mpro inhibitor. The synthesis was easy (UGI reaction) and it worked! 8/n

This is a combination of the fact that we removed substantial chunks of the original molecule to accommodate the electrophile. And also, might reflect less than optimal docking performance. Nevertheless, these covalent starting points can be further optimized. 7/n

We prospectively tested a few of these predictions against various kinases and succeeded in 5 out of 9 cases. A caveat I should note is that in all cases the new covalent inhibitors were less potent than their non-covalent parents. 6/n

We made both the database of predictions made against the PDB (renews weekly with new structures) publicly available. And you can also upload your own structures for covalentization: https://t.co/QAZOGFnhJv 5/n

In a retrospective benchmark of covalent kinase inhibitors, Covalentizer succeeded in ~40% of the cases to identify the original covalent inhibitor. We then applied it to the entire PDB and identified >1,500 high confidence predictions. 4/n

On the upside, if El Salvador succeeds, it will mostly spur larger experiments. Since it isn't enough to prove Bitcoin's status as a potential world currency if El Salvador succeeds; it's not large enough.

I hope the payoff is convex and good for El Salvador, regardless of the outcome.

I think both pro and anti-Bitcoin people should appreciate how much of an interesting experiment El Salvador is going to be. That said, it also feels a bit dystopian in the sense that a fairly poor, unstable country is basically being experimented on here.

According to a 2015 report, our maize consumption will be 8.6 million metric tonnes by 2050, assuming a constant per person consumption rate and steady production growth caused by the sale of approved seeds and fertilizer alternatives.
As a result, Kenya has a 1.2 million metric-tonne annual maize deficit, which is expected to increase annually as the country's population and demand for maize grows.

Kenya struggles to satisfy this demand with annual output of about 2.8M metric tonnes. Factors such as soil acidification caused by multi-year use of acidic fertilizers, a lack of access to improved seeds, and the effect of maize lethal necrosis factor all limit output.

Maize is the most widely consumed grain, accounting for 71% of total consumption. Kenyan maize consumption is estimated to be 100 kilograms per person per year.¬†This converts to around 35 million bags (about 4 million metric tonnes annually).

The "Big 4 Agenda" emphasizes the importance of long-term food security.¬†However, due to the heterogeneity and unfriendliness of the biophysical environment, the agricultural sector faces various challenges.

The good thing is, this was not the end of the story. There were other committees, even some consequences. And hopefully things have changed today. If you are a young PI and see wrongdoing, speak out. This sort of image fraud can' t be unseen. You *will* get support. /end

I was a young PI, in a supportive workplace quite insulated from Indian science politics. I faced no repercussion (and much appreciation) for calling them out. But I bought that some of *them* may have faced repercussions for speaking their mind. I no longer believe that. /cont

Because I don't for a moment believe that one single member of the committee genuinely thought there was no duplication. Not when it was highlighted and handed to them on a platter. There were other factors at work. /cont

Today I wonder, what about the others in that committee? Why did they all sign off on it? Some were senior, some mid-career then but senior now (one is among the top science admins in India). Do they regret their silence? /cont

It is not like the committee had to identify the duplicated images: that work had been done by whistleblowers. The committee only had to look at the images and say, same or not? They said no, and imputed malicious motives to the accuser. /cont

After so many years, I don't want to bring up names. My worry then was, how could the committee chair (a very senior man and familiar name) argue that these images (7 examples) were different? At this point one journal had already retracted the papers. /cont

What can be done? II- Consider whether the results make sense- And more importantly, consider whether the results would make sense if one held drastically different views - Finally, relax, most 'false findings' get corrected eventually, at least if they matter ...9/

What can be done?- Never blindly trust an abstract, a press release or a secondary source- Try to inspect the actual data (or the figures)- Accept it may well all be nonsense (even more so if the findings are extraordinary - sound science is often boring)8/
Peer review really doesn't help much. Enough said about that for now.7/

The problem of 'false research findings' can be particularly acute in crowded, competitive fields of research. We'll have to live with it in COVID19 research. Though one unprecedented issue is that likely 'false findings' often get considerable attention by the media.6/

The cartoon below provides a clever illustration of the problem. There are ways to try to control for 'multiple testing' within a single study. Though such corrections cannot be applied throughout the board (i.e. over multiple researchers and throughout time).5/ https://t.co/JgfFrZJRUW

The larger the number of hypothesis one tests, the higher the chance that one turns out to be significantly supported by the data. Slightly more formally, if one runs 20 tests between sets of random numbers with a significance level of Œ± = 0.05, we expect 1 to be significant.4/

Though, what it means is that each individual finding has a high probability of being incorrect. This can be because the analysis deployed was inadequate, but more often, because the association was just an artefactual finding, rather than being reflective of causality.3/

His thesis is difficult to argue against. Most published scientific findings are indeed likely false, whether they're peer-reviewed or not. This is in fact not such a major problem, as science is a process, and is largely self-corrective, arguably ineffectively so.2/

In the pre-COVID era, before John Ioannidis was a scientific outcast, he wrote what is arguably one the most provocative papers of all times. It's titled 'Why Most Published Research Findings are False'. It's a fantastic read, quite approachable.1/https://t.co/d6uJIKf1pL.

To conclude, the fact that there are different forces acting in conjunction implies that sinple arguments such as "there was an outbreak in summer, thus there is no seasonality" or "lockdown work / don't work, cases we highest before / after it" are unlikely to be robust.9/

To summarise, there are different forces at play that together push R up or down, with the epidemic growing whenever R > 1.  Below, I show three hypothetical countries with an epidemic under control (1 and 3) and one experiencing a surge (2).8/ https://t.co/0sJDfZgXl1

Behavioural changes leading to social distancing will decrease transmission. As those measures act in conjunction with the other forces, it can be difficult to estimate their effect. It is even worse for individual interventions (e.g. school closures).7/

Population immunisation through prior infection and vaccination will decrease R, as it reduces the susceptible population for the virus to spread. This is true even if the 'Herd Immunity Threshold" has not been attained.6/

Viruses will always be under selection to become more transmissible. This can be achieved through various mechanisms, such as increased viral load or by bypassing host immunisation (thus allowing immune escape lineages to exploit a larger host population .5/

Seasonality in the temperate zone can either increase of decrease R, with transmission being highest outside summer. The mechanisms are multiple and complex but include simple physical effects, such as enveloped RNA viruses tending to survive best in dry, cold air.4/

TLDR; software to estimate microbe-specific DNA concentrations using 16S/metagenomics data. Enjoy!

Final note - I *loved* working with this team (Brian Williamson & Jim Hughes) on this project. A super-motivated and talented PhD student (Brian, now graduated üé©) + an encouraging & wise senior faculty (Jim) = one happy, lucky junior faculty member (me!).

I would love for methods developers working with quantitative microbiome data ("relative" or "absolute") to think carefully about the assumptions that their methods make, and both communicate them to readers and consider whether they are supported by empirical evidence.
A plea: I would love for folks to use this method if they have questions about microbial load, but even more than that...

Side note: There's nothing stopping you from applying exactly the same idea to a relative abundance profile from shotgun data (eg based on mapping to a reference or via SCGs)... In fact, I'd love to hear from anyone who has this data and wants to give the method a go!
AND you can go eat doughnuts while the computer whirrs away! (I'm not a wet lab scientist, but I don't think you can eat donuts while developing primers... right?)
My hope is that using this is still easier, faster and more scalable than developing qPCR for every single bug you might want to quantify the load of.

Sounds pretty good, right?! The trade offs are that the method 1. is pretty computationally expensive2. produces very wide intervals.  Watch this space - we're working on both of these. (Hot take: we'll improve 2 before we can figure out 1)

In our validation study, we showed that our approach gives prediction intervals that control coverage at >=95% for 12 out of 13 taxa (held-out observations). How did 16S proportion x 16S total do? Zero out of 13. (Details in the paper) https://t.co/nCyezmfzQK
While our method needs taxon-specific qPCR data to work, it has the benefit of producing interval estimates that, well, work. Bold claim, right?!
While the approach is more general, this paper discusses using qPCR data for a subset of taxa (in our eg, we had 13) alongside 16S data.
To get more reasonable predictions, you need to take this differential detection-efficiency issue into account. That's just what our method does! https://t.co/J2I2WFtfY0

Comparing the two data types shows that this assumption doesn't hold. e.g., G. vaginalis (light blue) is typically underdetected by 16S compared to qPCR, while P. micra (grey) is typically overdetected. https://t.co/NdeYNeBJUr

Finally one needs a diversity of teams in each task. These things are fiddly and complex; they break in complex ways. I really appreciate SPI-M and the transparency of their models. And ‚Ä¶ stop benchingmarking scenario models to data or *at least* indicate that it is a scenario

(Eg ideally I‚Äôd like a better - lower granularity - geographic scenario model to my taste - as well cruder regional ones. But I‚Äôm not a scenario modeller and I appreciate the complexity of just getting a scenario model ‚Äúin zone‚Äù - meaning it will model reasonably existing data)

Now - the counter factual in this is ‚Ä¶ hard and the appropriateness of the scenario model (what parameter combinations did they look at? What aspects of reality did they ignore?) is key. *plenty* to argue about

This means ‚Ä¶ scenario models are *not there to be benchmarked to outcomes*. It‚Äôs not the ‚Ä¶ goal of these models. The goal is inform decision making so the question is better asked ‚Äúwas a good decision made with these models‚Äù.

For scenario models often they are deliberately asked to use ‚Äúreasonable worse case‚Äù thinking - this English phrase has to be mapped to parameters and some parameters are not explored because they don‚Äôt impact the decision space too much
And I am leaving out causal models (v useful when they can grip a problem) and deep learning (is it model? What has it learnt?).

There are in some fields ‚Äúsimulation models‚Äù where the model of reality is good enough that running models with different configurations is meaningfully connected with error bars to reality. Not one for infectious epidemiology :)

(No one - no one - can in their head work up what happens wuth exponential growth of x of infection but increasing vaccination of y at this age stratification. You need a model and computer to play around with ‚Ä¶ scenarios)

Then there are scenario models. These are ‚Äúfor this necessarily crude model of reality what could happen in different scenarios‚Äù. These are not forecasts nor predictions; they help humans get their head around the complex decision space in front of them.

Forecast models are still present (little coloured fans at the end of charts) but often don‚Äôt get much heat; not least because they are often quite good and then most ‚Äúhard‚Äù forecasts can‚Äôt go beyond 7 days or so

Success here is twofold - how good is your prediction and - as important- how calibrated is your uncertainty - if you say 90% of the time the value shoukd within this range how often does this happen?

Then there are forecast models; for this understanding - indeed sometimes a very agnostic view - can you predict what happens over the next 1,2, 4, 7 days? Indeed given laggy data can you accurately predict what‚Äôs today‚Äôs true numbers will be (so called ‚Äúnowcast‚Äù)
Success here is making inferences of parameters which are robust - if you assign a value to a lineage it should be the same (given no GxE effect) elsewhere

Interestingly one has variance aspects of these models to fit data but the variation is dealing with two things- ‚Äútrue‚Äù variance - from counts to random sampling process to variance between the mismatch between models and reality - eg all a local authority experiences the same

These are the models I‚Äôm most familiar with - eg we observe these sequences, what is the most likely evolutionary history; we observe these case with these genomes in these places; what is the most likely growth rates attributable to the lineages
The first is an inference model. For some understanding of reality, these are estimated parameters that explain observed, existing data.

A reminder that this is a humanity vs virus fight; all humans need to work together, and the real population unit to consider, slightly awesomely, is everyone on the planet. We've got a long way to go, but we do have the tools to get there.

The support for vaccine roll out by @gavi, G7 pledges (though details, details, details - how much actual vaccines, when being the most important) is great, but there is a still a long road worldwide.

Most of the non-developed world has a longer horizon, and we should, sadly, expect yet another evolution of the virus at some point in some place. This virus is not going to magically go away; our best solution is managed endemic virus with regular boosters for people at risk

Balancing when to have that final exit wave is going to be interesting and beyond the obvious - vaccinate as fast as possible - I think some care needs to taken on September/October, and the number of unvaccinated at risk people in each country then will be key.

For Europe, it will be important to get to School holidays so that there is less mixing and more outdoor activity over the holidays before Delta rises (indeed, this much the strategy in the UK with the delay of 4 weeks).

The differential transmission impact of 1st doses from Alpha to Delta is also going to be headache; countries that can easily control transmission of Alpha partly due to vaccination might find it far far harder to control Delta; Canada is particular at risk here.

More complex is how Delta travels through the world. It has already ravaged India, with large recorded deaths and probably far higher unrecorded (I am not an expert on COVID in India, so this is what I get from colleagues and Twitter).
I am less concerned though by the UK; the vaccination strategy works, the ability to see and quantify a new dangerous variant has happened, and an appropriate response looks in the works.

A problem in communication here is going to be that there is going to be a number of people going to hospital over the summer with COVID in the UK, in any plan. What want is this to be within the bounds of the UK healthcare service (NHS).

It's worth stressing that *whenever* a country opens up fully (eg, Israel with B.1.1.7) there will be an "exit wave" and indeed one of the complications in the UK has been how much Delta vs how much stage 3 transmission change has occured over the last 4 weeks.

This changes the calculus of how fast transmission will happen in the UK relative to vaccination rates, and because of this the UK Government looks likely to delay the final stage of reopening. This is ... sensible with far lower risks, and has paths ratcheting open.

The virus has continued to evolve over the last 18 months. The dominant strain in the UK, Delta, (B.1.617.2, first identified in India) is both *more* transmissible than the previously evolved Alpha strain (B.1.1.7) and, frustratingly, takes less notice of a single vaccine dose

22/ Our findings also challenge the simple pairwise rules often invoked to explain microbial community assembly and suggest that nonlinear interactions across trophic levels - for example, driven by consumer trait variability - are important determinants of community structure.
21/ The number and magnitude of these nonlinear relationships may be critical feedbacks stabilizing the coexistence of many bacterial prey species in natural microbial communities.
20/ Thus, trait variability at one trophic level may have complex and nonlinear downstream effects on other trophic levels in the wild.

19/ Overall, trait variability in the ciliate promoted a clear competitive outcome at the consumer level, but the effects of consumer trait variability and competition on the prey community were non-additive.
18/ Ciliate trait variability strengthened the non-additivity of how prey defense traits influenced prey community assembly in the presence of the competing consumer.

17/ Prey community assembly was mediated through key prey functional traits related to defense and resource use. Approximately 50% of the variance in prey species abundances could be explained by the distribution of defense and growth traits across individual prey species.

We also see that tenacious bacteria have the highest chance to be transferred vertical (parent-child), so likely to be inherited, but this group also has the highest chance to be lost after antibiotic treatments

Dispersal patterns can be separated into spatiopersistent (good at geo & individual), heredipersistent (good at family & individual) and tenacious (good at everything). Bacteroidiota are often tenacious (could be called "clingy bacteria" as well ;) ) https://t.co/rozSvWq0mI

Having had data from individual hosts (time series), families and > 10 countries, we can track persistence at the individual, family and geographic level. This showed several meaningful correlations, dispersal patterns become visible https://t.co/Sil1vDAXpX

anyway i wonder what the internet did to the effective population size of memes
even the slightest reproductive advantageous mutant can rapidly take over

in an untreated hiv infection there is a huge population of infected cells, and every day most of those cells die and are replaced by newly infected cellsevery possible point mutation to the hiv genome occurs multiple times weekly, giving selection many chances to operate
what it does have that they don't, is an enormous effective population sizethis doesn't change the mutation rate, but it makes natural selection terribly efficient
and it is true that it mutates very fast compared to us, or even to some other virusesbut it's not much faster than other RNA viruses which aren't nearly as talented evolvers
hiv is famously very good at evolving to resist drugs and escape immune attackthis is often presented as an inevitable consequence of its remarkably high mutation rate

When Canada celebrates 175, there are 2 possible speeches an Indigenous leader will give. One can be written today and will resemble speeches at the last bday. The other begins ‚Äú22 years ago we made a set of dramatic policy shifts and undertook a concrete set of actions‚Ä¶‚Äù
STRUCTURES. Find the right type of advice on how our organization does things and how the community perceives them.
POLICIES. Run an organizational audit. Uncover unconscious biases in our policies. Be intentional in instituting change.

PEOPLE. Explore with purpose EDID: Equity, Diversity, Inclusion and Decolonization. Take stock of our organization and make an effort make sure it is inclusive. And it‚Äôs ok to be intentional and deliberate in being inclusive.
CEREMONIES. Make deliberate efforts to celebrate and welcome Indigenous culture, participate in ceremonies, and interact meaningfully with Indigenous peoples.
So what can we as an organization do? Four key things we need to focus on:

What Indigenous peoples have been asking for since 1960 is being equal partners in a co-created world. He shared a brief history since 1960 when Indigenous peoples got the right to vote and entered into the franchise that is Canada.

Here‚Äôs what we learned: In Canada, we are treating reconciliation as a state of mind. But it‚Äôs more than that. It‚Äôs an action. Reconciliation is the co-creation that we do together and make equal contributions to. We must be equals and move forward together.

Zoom, Tweets, Slack, and good ol' fashioned email has meant we have stayed doing excellent science across @embl but... science needs people and creativity, and that needs diverse ideas from many people. I can't wait for all of @embl to be travel friendly again.

I miss taking friends and colleagues from @embl to the Red Lion pub at Hinxton, explaining the right temperature for a pint of British Bitter and then heading into Cambridge for us to discuss science in Cambridge College room from the 16th century

I miss hefeweizen in the aching cool Hamburg Gaswerks hotel, post an education in Xray, SAXS and free electron lasers from friends @EMBLHamburg, chatting data flows, European football and occasional idea (the best ones which leads to nature papers and patents!).

I miss glorious and impossible to imagine cheese and charcuterie plates @EMBLGrenoble as crystal soaking and automated X-ray placement robots are explained to me over the world's most complicated cheese selection.

I miss Aperol spritz in the courtyard of Hotel Ponte Sisto as friends from @EMBLRome gather around and I get educated in neuroscience whilst I pass on hard won lessons from the practical end of data science, and then over the bridge to Trastevere
I miss walking through El Born with colleagues from @EMBLBarcelona, heading the Xampaignet to meet old friends from @CRGenomica and @BSC_CNS to talk about science and life over tapas and cava

<sigh>. I miss... hefeweizen in the Aldstadt of Heidelberg, after a busy day chit-chatting @EMBLHeidelberg seeing colleagues and friends navigating the cobbles to join us around a sunny table, Neckar in the background, a nice Spatzle dish ahead of us, talking science
The purpose of life has been changed along the way of life. But, the one thing never change that I know is I want to stay beside of you along our journey.

The commitment of actual vaccines from the developed world is a necessary part of the solution and this is good for both humane reasons - many people will die in awful situations without this - and for selfish, narrow reasons - we want less of this virus circulating.

But the elephant in the room is that with even faster transmitting variants, the global race between vaccination and transmission has shifted strongly towards transmission. This is awful and heartbreaking; it is most obvious in India.

It will be interesting to see how other countries adjust plans or not over this summer, and some of the countries which have done so well on suppression (Japan) or border control (Australia and New Zealand) will be running bigger risks until they are appropriately vaccinated.

Stepping back from the slightly feverish details of the Delta variant in the UK and change to UK plan, the UK, along with many developed countries are in a good place because vaccines continue to work in particular vs severe disease. Basically : Vaccines work, plan to this.

(this is because plenty of reasonable worse case scenario parameters of February - of vaccine effectiveness and of vaccine uptake in particular - have turned out in our favour. However one can't just weigh these "in our favour" vs Delta variant "faster transmission" trivially)

Scenario modellers and decision makers informed by scenarios now have their work cut out for them over the next period. My personal framing is to accept that we need a new plan, but that this new plan *might* be pretty close to the old plan.

We are, in effect, in a different space in the UK from Jan 2021 or October 2020, though still the fundamentals of exponential increase can easily make a very small percentage of people being hospitalised a big problem for the NHS.

Taking some of the earliest hotspots in the UK as exemplars, one can see how vaccination has changed things - the case numbers of double vaccinated older groups have not gone up anywhere near as fast as in previous waves, and hospitalisations are (currently) lowish.

For the epidemiological data, one needs time and numbers to be able to work out impact on severe disease, and the lack of numbers - largely a good thing! - also means distinguishing different vaccines types - Pfzier vs AZ in the UK and doses impacts complex)

(Again, so complex to handle with real data! Remember that the laboratory antibody assays is one arm of the immune system; the T-cell arm, probably more involved in severe disease, in fact largely an *overreaction* is not assayed here. Hence severe disease can be quite different

Bottom line is that overall 6 wk not non-inferior. So as a general rule, stick with 12 wk.DAIR ‚Äì 12wk better than 6wk (not only is 6wk not non-inferior, but the data says it is worse)

Also not clear if the primary outcome was triggered if samples taken at 2nd stage surgery were positive ‚Äì these patients would usually go on to at least another 6 wks abx and actual functional and curative outcomes may be similar to the 12 wk group.

Failure more common for all 3 groups with 6 wk vs 12 wk (although most pronounced for DAIR).Most notably for 2-stage, 12 wk doubles time not just on Abx, but also time with the morbidity of having a spacer. https://t.co/pXNPOdPE1K

Our analysis thus identified TREM2high m‚≤™ expansion in obese mouse and human kidneys pointing to obesity-instructed m‚≤™s as a local determinant of the immune response to kidney injury 9/ https://t.co/VTQXnS5JYH

Both models had multiple resident/infiltrating m‚≤™s, as in healthy mice. While no LYVE1high m‚≤™s were identified in either disease model, resident m‚≤™s expanded in both. A distinct Trem2high subset expanded with disease and age in HFD, with a signature resembling LAMs in adipose https://t.co/BSPklYARMq

Using cell census of high-fat diet (HFD) fed obese, diabetic kidney and a genetic model (BTBR ob/ob), we compared mouse disease signatures with that of early human disease. The mouse proximal tubule showed transcriptional changes (Pck1,Gsta2,PPAR) preceding overt histology 7/ https://t.co/XpzdouCK1A

Comparative analysis revealed: while broad cell classes correspond cross-species, each species has its own granular subsets which must be considered when translating insights. Some of these differences may be driven by divergent cell-type specificities of transcription factors 6/ https://t.co/ztTOSchAL8

The TREM2high macrophages were rare by scRNA-seq, even rarer when confirmed in-situ, without a matching counterpart in adult mouse kidney. Both LYVE1high (CCL3- and CCL3+) and TREM2high subsets were shared across tissues. Coronal sections captured all mouse subsets 5/ https://t.co/1k6SYfuW60

In adult human kidney, we identified (1)multiple LYVE1high macrophage subsets characterized by a homeostatic signature, matching a hilar-specific mouse Lyve1high subset, (2)TREM2high macrophage subsets with signatures similar to lipid/scar-associated m‚≤™ seen in adipose/liver 4/ https://t.co/R3qxnK7a7G

The ICE was very nicely conserved, more than the 4 previously described CJIE1-4 Insertion Elements. We also checked the distribution of all five MGEs and the 3 major plasmid categories in the 7176 Campylobacter genomes (5829 jejuni and 1347 coli) 8/n

Firstly, the ICE contained 3 potential CRISPR arrays distributed over the ICE, rather than just one downstream of the cas genes. A tracrRNA was in the spacer array 30 kb upstream of cas9 . All of these spacer arrays were small, usually <5 repeats (common for Campylobacter) 7/n

We called this one CampyICE1. There were already examples of CRISPR-Cas on plasmids (type IV, some type I) and mobile genetic elements (Type I in Vibrio), but we could not find any examples of Type II Cas9 on a MGE. That was only the beginning of the "unique" features 6/n

The new variant Cas9 clustered separately from other Campylobacter/Helicobacter Cas9 proteins. It was in a different genomic context, and lacked genes encoding Cas1/Cas2. Looking at the genomic context suggested it was located on an integrative conjugative element (ICE) 5/n

The distribution studies were done using BLASTN, but later BLASTP searches showed a rare Cas9 variant. Did some more specific searches and found the additional cas9 gene in 226 of the 7176 C. jejuni/coli genome collection 4/n

However, I was not able to source any of those beans for testing.This project will probably take longer to see any movement than my #BlueBeanProject did.

For a bright orange, I need carotenoids. Specifically, beta-carotene for its carrot-orange color.So far, I haven't found anything that fits.I did come across a photo of some beans which seemed to have red speckles as a separate trait from brown/black speckles on a pale base.

If I combined the "yellow" and "red" colors common in beans to make "orange", it would really be mixing yellow-brown and red-brown to make orange-brown which is mostly just brown.It might be a pretty shade, but it won't be the orange I'm looking for.
What I want is an orange dry bean. Why? The same reason I wanted a blue one. It doesn't seem to exist and would be pretty.

The red-brown in beans is also a flavonoid, an anthocyanin specifically. They can be "red", but certainly not tomato-red.I'm growing some red beans called "Red Wombat" from @UrsulaV, to see if their pigment pattern stays the same in a new growing area. (I forgot to photograph).

The "yellow" flavonoids (chalcones?) give us the yellow-brown seen in beans vs the sunflower-yellow from carotenoids seen in... sunflowers.These beans are "ALE Yellow", a bush bean from Aster Lane Edibles (a small now-closed Canadian seed company). https://t.co/rFVMsGmLgH

For an unrelated bean project... I've been looking for beans with color derived from carotenoids. These compounds produce the bright yellow, orange, and red colors seen in many fruits.All the bean colors I've seen or read research on seem to be derived from flavonoid pigments. https://t.co/Secs4yDgIV

I'm not getting into it right now, but the second part of this project is the production of an annotated version of ABP. Lush speculated about many things that we understand better today, and his intuition was often good. I have no timeline for that project, it may never be done.

There are also typos in the original text - do I correct or leave those? I'm not big on "[sic]" because I think they're typesetting errors, not Lush spelling errors. So many decisions. Once it's "finished", everything will go on GitHub.

is a mess. The table of contents needs a lot of work to match the ABP style. Most of this is just cleanup, but it all takes time. Then I need to print the whole thing for blue pencil editing and decisions about the final typographic style. The latter will be a long process.

tweaked by hand. I've also got a narrow, vertical figure that's going to need work so that text flows properly around it. Some lines that LaTeX is indenting shouldn't be. Nothing is indexed yet. References aren't presented in a consistent style across the book. The frontmatter

Step 9, creating the document, is OK most of the time, but every now and then a table will take some troubleshooting to fix. I've got LOTS of overful hboxes and lots of tables don't fit on the page. Some equations run off, too. Fixable with time, but many table headers need to be

I'm not even trying to recreate the "use dots instead of spaces" style. I'm sure it's possible, but it's not high-priority for me right now. decimals are typeset without leading zeroes, not sure when that convention changed.

The tables (Step 8) are where things get hairy. The headers are often complex - they can be set in LaTeX, but I'm slow at it. The way the OCR chunks up the text you can't really paste in table contents. Many tables are not numbered and have no headers or captions.

Step 6 - the basic typesetting - isn't too bad, but I'm learning where the gaps are in my knowledge of LaTeX. Step 7 is mostly cut-and-paste, but ABP used smallcaps to set all of the figure captions. That's not a common choice today.

didn't use a consistent style throughout the book for references, etc. In this first iteration I'm trying to faithfully recreate his original work, so that means also getting these details as close to correct as I can.

Step 5 takes a long time, for several reasons: the copy I scanned has reader-added notes, underlines, etc., which confused the OCR; there are many references to non-US authors and journals, so spelling has to be checked very carefully and accent marks typeset properly; and Lush

Lush had his own style of writing, and he often used italics for emphasis. You lose that information when you just dump text and have to go back to the original document anyway. It also makes it easier to get footnotes in the right place.

For step 4, I'm using Texmaker on Windows 10 for the typesetting. It works pretty well. There's probably a way to save the OCRed text from Adobe directly into a text file, but I prefer to go a page at a time by hand because it's easier for me to keep up with things that way.
